<div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-two-thirds palm-one-whole">
<h2>How to Sign up for, and begin transcribing, using the CSI online transcription system.</h2>
<p>First, sign up as a Transcriber with FreeCEN.</p>
<p>Second, <a href="https://csindexing.com/instructions.php" title="https://csindexing.com/instructions.php">follow the instructions here</a>: choose 'FreeCEN' as your project.</p>
<p>Third, follow the instructions in this document.&#160; For the database to be fully searchable, we all need to record the census information in the same way. This page has the details of what to put where in your transcription. It also includes some general principles and information on the abbreviations that we need to use.
</p>
    <h2>The guiding principles of transcribing</h2>
    <h3>Work as quickly as possible</h3>
    <p>Without sacrificing typing accuracy, get each transcription done as quickly as possible, recording difficult to read entries as your best guess. Behind you will be a Proofreader who will go through your transcription record by record and attempt to resolve any problems. Behind them is a Validator. So two more, experienced people will get to look at those difficult to read entries.</p>
    <p>Having said that, it is also important to pace yourself: pause before you actually feel tired; get up from your computer and do something else for a while.</p>
    
    <h3>The ‘as is’ rule</h3>
    <p>The general rule is to transcribe ‘as is’, including spelling mistakes and other errors by the enumerator. The task is to take the information that is hand written on the census page and set it out so that it can be stored and searched in a database. The researcher will then interpret the data, not us. However tempting it may be to ‘correct’ what the enumerator has written, it is dangerous to presume that we can know for certain what the entry should have been.The general rule is to transcribe ‘as is’, including spelling mistakes and other errors by the enumerator. The task is to take the information that is hand written on the census page and set it out so that it can be stored and searched in a database. The researcher will then interpret the data, not us. However tempting it may be to ‘correct’ what the enumerator has written, it is dangerous to presume that we can know for certain what the entry should have been.<br />There are a few specific exceptions to this rule which will be described below. These are mainly to do with standardising the way the data is recorded.</p>
    <p>There are a few specific exceptions to this rule which will be described below. These are mainly to do with standardising the way the data is recorded.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">The main exception to the <q>as is</q> rule are:</p>
    <ul class="needsSpace">
      <li><strong>Expand all dittos</strong>: Enumerators often used “ditto”, or “do” or “ '' ” to indicate that an entry such as surname should be the same as the one above. While this works on the written page, it does not work in a database where the record for every individual has to stand alone. So always type the entry in full.</li>
      <li><strong>Do not use a <q>?</q>
</strong> in any field other than Y, Notes or Query fields. In other words, do not use a question mark for something that you cannot read or where a place of birth or a surname, for example, is recorded as “unknown” or “NK” or anything similar (type what you see). The only exception to this is that the Notes or Query fields can contain a <q>?</q> to indicate a doubt about an entry or when transcribing a "?" in the Census record.</li>
<li><strong>Expand <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#abbrev">regularised abbreviations</a>
</strong> seen in the text, for example Enumerators were instructed to abbreviate common occupations for the 1841 census. Thus “FS” was used for “Female Servant”, “J” for “Journeyman” and so on. Some enumerators continued to use these on later census returns. Where these are abbreviations that had fixed meanings, they should be entered in full.
    </li>
</ul>
    <h3>Case</h3>
    <p>
You may wish to type your entries in lower-case letters, to save keystrokes and so time: the appropriate capital (upper-case) letters will be put in automatically before your file becomes part of the database. Please use the capitalisation in the document for Census notes. Please use capitals for acronyms such as GP, MCRS.
</p>
    <h3>Blank and duplicate pages</h3>
    <p>If you are show the 'General instructions' page or similar page, or an enumerator has left a page blank, do not record anything, use the 'report a problem' button on the top left of the screen, select "Nothing to transcribe" from the drop-down choices, and then click&#160; the "Report the problem" button. On the next screen, it will tell you that the problem has been reported. Click the 'I'm ready to index another' button, and you will be taken to the next page to index.&#160; You may face a small run of such pages all together, just keep marking them as 'Nothing to transcribe' and it will mean you and others are not shown them again.</p>
<p>If you are sure that you have received two copies of the same page, then only transcribe the first. On the second page, use the 'report a problem' button, choose "Duplicate" from the drop-down choices, and then click the "Report the problem" button.&#160; An admin will check that it is a duplicate, and if it is, will withdraw the image so it is not offered to transcribers again.&#160;&#160; Click the 'I'm ready to index another' button, and you will be taken to the next page to index.</p>
<h3>Sample Page</h3>
<p>You may be shown a sample page with typeset handwriting.&#160; Do not record anything, use the 'report a problem' button on the top left of the screen, select "Nothing to transcribe" from the drop-down choices, and then click  the "Report the problem" button. On the next screen, it will tell you that the problem has been reported. Click the 'I'm ready to index another' button, and you will be taken to the next page to index.</p>
    <h3>Learn the lingo</h3>
    <p>You will be entering text directly into a database, which will produce a spreadsheet for Proofreading. We use the terms fields and columns, records and rows, interchangably.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />
  
  </div> 

  <div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-two-thirds palm-one-whole field">
    <h2>The fields in detail</h2>

    <div id="header">

      <h3>Header Information</h3>
      <div class="push--bottom">Return to <a href="#pageNav">On this page</a> </div>

      <h4>Civil Parish</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong>
</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Look for this at the top-left of each census page.</p>
      <p>Do not confuse the Civil Parish with the <em>Ecclesiastical Parish</em> which you may find at the top-right of the census page.&#160;You can help the Proofreader by leaving a note, in Transcribers’ Notes, at the start and end of each Ecclesiastical parish.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Shipping returns:</h5>
      <p>If the port where the return was handed in is known, then enter the name of that port and the relevant county.  If the port where the return was handed in is not known, then enter the name of the port and county where the return was issued.
In either case the required format is the port name followed by the Chapman County Code, as in “Fraserburgh ABD”.</p>
      
      

      <h4>Enumeration District</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 3 numerals plus an optional suffix, <strong>###a</strong>
</li>
        <li>The default entry is “0” (zero)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>This will be found on the first of the introductory pages to each Enumeration District (ED). If there is no identifiable ED number then enter “0” (zero). Note that the first District of a Census Piece may not necessarily be ED 1.</p> 
      <p>If there is a letter after the ED number on the introductory page, then enter this too.</p>
    
      <h5>Guidance for Institutions and Shipping Returns:</h5>
      <p>The returns for institutions and shipping usually come at the end of an Enumeration District, and appear in a different format without an ED number. In this case the entry in this field should take the form <strong>0#n</strong> where <strong>n</strong> is taken from the following list:</p>
      <ol>
        <li> Barracks &amp; Military Quarters</li>
        <li> HM Ships, at Home</li>
        <li> Workhouses &amp; Pauper Schools</li>
        <li> Hospitals (Sick, Convalescent, Incurables)</li>
        <li> Lunatic Asylums</li>
        <li> Prisons</li>
        <li> Certified Reformatory &amp; Industrial Schools</li>
        <li> Merchant Vessels &amp; Lighthouses</li>
        <li> Schools</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Thus, a workhouse would be entered as “0#3”. Note the need for the literal # sign! (On a Mac, this can be typed by holding down alt and 3 together.)</p>
      <p>In the unlikely case of an institution being listed, for example, as “Enumeration District 2a”, the ED number would be entered in the form <strong>2#n</strong>, where <strong>n</strong> is again taken from the list above. If the type of Institution is not listed, then <strong>n</strong> is “0” (zero).</p>
      <p>The returns for institutions and shipping should always be&#160;transcribed in the same sequence as they appear on the census page.</p>
      <p>Some Institutions used a booklet in which each page has the individual lines numbered from 1 to 25: do not type these numbers anywhere.</p>
      

      <h4>Folio Number</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to four numerals plus an optional suffix, <strong>####a</strong>
</li>
        <li>The default entry is “0” (zero)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The Folio Number is hand-stamped at the top right-hand corner of every odd-numbered page.</p>
      <p>Folio Numbers start from 1 at the beginning of a Census Piece and progressively increase, regardless of changes to the Enumeration District.</p>
      <p>Sometimes pages were missed (although the number may have been pencilled in later) or even whole books may not have been numbered. Suffix letters are very rare. Where a Folio Number is missing from its normal position, then enter “0” (zero) against the first line of the un-numbered folio and do not make another entry until a Folio Number re-appears.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Shipping Returns:</h5>
      <p>If the return does not have folio numbering please enter “0” (zero) against the first line of the return.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Scotland:</h5>
      <p>Folio Numbers were not used in Scotland.  The <strong>1841</strong> Census used book numbers and the <strong>1851</strong> Census used volume numbers. Any book or volume number should be recorded in this field (which is otherwise set to zero).  For 1841, the book number will normally be found at the bottom of the first page of each Enumeration District.  It is the circled number at the bottom, under the ED number, but was entered in pencil and is often quite faint. If it is not there, then it may appear on the index card above the first page. For 1851, the volume number is listed on the index card prior to the start of each parish.</p>
      <p>No other reference numbers appear in either the <strong>1861</strong> or <strong>1871</strong> Censuses.  For these years please enter “0” (zero) in this field against the first line of each Enumeration District.</p>
      

      <h4>Page Number</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong>&#160;[REMOVE and can be up to four numerals, <strong>#### note to self: need to do auto-check on this on loading]</strong>
</li>
        <li>The default entry is “0” (zero)</li>
      </ul>
    
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The Page Number is pre-printed on each census page.&#160;The page numbers are generally in the top centre for 1841 and 1851, and at the top alternating left and right for 1861 and 1871.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Shipping Returns:</h5>
      <p>There may be no page numbers, in which case enter “0” (zero).</p>
      

    </div> 
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <div id="address">
      <h3>Schedule &amp; Address Details</h3>
      <div class="push--bottom">Return to <a href="#pageNav">On this page</a> </div>

      <h4>Schedule Number (awaiting revision from Geoff)</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong>&#160;[REMOVE??? and can be up to 3 numerals plus an optional suffix, <strong>###a]</strong>
</li>
        <li>The default entry is “0” (zero)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>This is the first column on most census pages.  Schedule Numbers were used to identify the start of each separate household.  Enter the schedule number on the first line of each new household.  A suffix should be entered where it is present on the Census page. The suffix may be a single letter, but never a fraction.</p>
      <p>In the FreeCEN process, this field provides the ‘trigger’ to recognise each separate household or building.  A value <em>must</em> be entered in this field for every new household, and “0” (zero) should be entered where, for whatever reason, the enumerator failed to enter a schedule number for a new household.  For instance, where the Enumerator has entered two separate families, each with its own Head, under a single schedule number, a zero should be entered on the first line of the second family.</p>
      <p><mark>We know that some coords have allowed 34a, say, where an additional Sch Num is needed, instead of 0 (zero) — is this acceptable? It is not as-is, but … ??? WHAT DO WE WANT, GOING FORWARDS?</mark>
</p>
      <p>Please note that Schedule numbers were not used in the <strong>1841</strong> census, and “0” (zero) should be entered on the first line of each household.</p>
      <p>All Schedule Numbers must be accounted for: where the enumerator has, for whatever reason, omitted a schedule number, enter that number in this field, and put <strong>n</strong> in column "Special Use".</p>
      <p>Enter zero in this field against each house recorded by the enumerator as uninhabited or being built.  Sometimes the enumerator entered the number of such buildings on the same line as the next household.  These must be entered separately in the transcription, with one line for each such building. For further guidance on how to transcribe such entries, please refer to column "Special Use"&#160;below.</p>
      <p><span style="color: rgb(60, 120, 180);">Guidance for Institutions and Shipping Returns:</span>
</p>
      <p>Schedule numbers were not used in these returns. Treat an Institution as a single household (even if a very large one) that may contain several individuals identified as “Head”, “Wife”, etc. Simply enter “0” (zero) on the first line of the Institution.</p>  
      <p>Transcribe an Institution in the sequence that the people are recorded in the census pages. This means that it is not always possible to maintain the usual family groupings where, for example, a Lighthouse Station has the staff listed first and then the various wives and children.</p>

      <h4>House Number</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Type what you see. Use ‘keyboard special characters’ to enter fractions: “2½ Colliery Row” would be entered as “22½” in this column and Colliery Row in column"Address"</li>
<li>Use for house name (and number, if both are present) e.g. Lowood Farm, Highwood Road would be entered as 'Lowood Farm' in this column and Highwood Road in column "Address", or The Hollies, 4 Highwood Road would be entered as 'The Hollies, 4' in this column and Highwood Road in column "Address".</li>
      </ul> 
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>House numbers may be found in the column on the census page which is associated with the street name. Enter the house number in this fieldon the first line of the household, but leave blank where no house number is given. House numbers were not generally recorded in the <strong>1841</strong> census.</p>
      <p>Where two households are separated by a single tick (/) then that means new household, same address. The address of the previous household (if given) should be re-entered for the new household.</p>

      <h4>Address (awaiting clarification from Geoff esp. re shipping)</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 30 characters</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Copy the address as recorded — even if it looks wrong! The address should be entered only once, on the first line of the household, even where the household is split over two pages. Where the address is given only at the top of the second page, then move the address to the beginning of the household.</p>
      <p>If no address is recorded, then enter “-” (a hyphen). Do not assume that the address is necessarily the same as for the previous household, unless a repeater word or mark (such as “ditto” or “do”) has clearly been recorded.</p>
      <p>Transcribe any supplementary information after the street name, as in “High&#160;Street, Anchor Hotel”.&#160;&#160;</p>
<p>Do not expand abbreviations such as "St", "Rd" or "Terr".</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Shipping Returns:</h5>
      <p>Enter the address for a Shipping Return as the vessel name in brackets (parentheses) followed by the home port, the port of origin, if given, e.g. “(Prince Consort) Aberdeen”. [??? any changes needed?&#160; We can add a field for ship name, if that is wanted]</p>
      <p><span style="color: rgb(60, 120, 180);">Guidance for Scotland:</span>
</p>
      <p>In <strong>1841</strong>, if an address is written at the top of the page, and only at the top, then it can be used for the other households on that page.</p>
      <p>From <strong>1851 onwards</strong>, an address can be copied for other households in the same building, but not between buildings unless the enumerator has used a repeater word or mark (such as “ditto”). If the next building has no address given, enter “-” (a hyphen).</p>

      <h4>Special Use</h4>
<p><span style="color: rgb(60, 120, 180);">Requirements:</span>
</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character ([<strong>x</strong>, ]<strong>u</strong>, <strong>b</strong>, <strong>n</strong>, or <strong>v</strong>), or leave the column blank. Any other entry will be rejected in the FreeCEN process as invalid.</li>
      </ul> 
      <h5>Guidance:</h5> 
      <p>Alternatively, one of the characters <strong>b</strong>, <strong>u</strong>, <strong>n</strong>, or <strong>v</strong> may be entered in this column.  If any one of these characters is entered in this column, then any information entered in the following fields, but not the notes fields will be ignored.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter <strong>b</strong> if the enumerator has recorded a house being built</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>u</strong> if the enumerator has recorded an uninhabited house</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>v</strong> if the enumerator indicates that the family are away or visiting</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>n</strong> to show that a Schedule Number is missing, one line for each unused number.  This proves the omission to be in the census return, and not made at the transcription!</li> 
        <li>Also enter <strong>n</strong> in the case of deleted addresses, as for example where a note on the census page states that “Three schedules numbered for the Light House not required, being provided with a schedule from the Trinity Board”. In this instance, type the address as “Light House”, put <strong>n</strong> in this field and the note in column "Census notes".</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Please note that where an enumerator has grouped vacant premises as a single entry (such as “4b” or “2u”), each of the premises must be treated as a separate household with its own schedule number, even though this may be zero.  Sometimes the enumerator started the next household on the same line as vacant premises. You should always enter them on separate rows.</p>
      <p>Similarly, vacant premises cannot occur within a household, for instance where the enumerator may have added “1u”, having previously forgotten it.  Normally, you should enter the vacancy immediately after the household with residents.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Shipping:</h5>
      <p>Occasionally you may find a (foreign) ship that is named but with no crew details. Enter <strong>v</strong> in this field and put any extra information in the "CensusNotes" field: for example, the (Louise Frederick) came from Norway, had five crew on board who were not named, nor were any personal details provided — you enter “(Louise Frederick) Norway” in column "Address", “v” in this column, and “five crew, unnamed” in column "Census notes".</p>
<h1>Address Query</h1>
<p>Enter x in H2 where you have doubts about the interpretation of any of the columns E, F or G, either because you cannot read or for other reasons. Write a brief comment in the Transcriber Notes column to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?house number”&#160; .</p>
    </div>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />
    
    <div id="person">
      <h3>Personal Details</h3>
      <div class="push--bottom">Return to <a href="#pageNav">On this page</a> </div>

      <h4>Surname</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong>&#160;</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="guide">Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Copy the Surname as it appears on the census page — even if it looks wrong, or is known to be wrong!  Any repeater word or mark (such as “ditto” or “do”) must be expanded in full.</p>
      <p>You <em>must</em> enter something in this column for every person in a household. If a surname is not given, enter “-” (a hyphen). If the enumerator has put “unknown” or something similar, transcribe as “(Unknown)”.</p>
      <p>Please note that the Surname is the field which researchers will generally be searching on, so you should always use your best endeavours to interpret correctly what is written on the census page.  If it is unclear (because it is poorly written, smudged or covered by marks) or where it is uncertain (because the individual letters are difficult to interpret), then raise a query in the "Name Query" column to bring it to the attention of the Proofreader and put an explanatory note in the "Transcriber Notes" column.</p>

      <h5>Guidance for Scotland:</h5>
      <p>??? NEED TO CHECK WITH DEVELOPERS Sometimes, the Scottish census will record two surnames for a wife.  Enter both of the names, separated by a space, /, space, as in “murray&#160;/&#160;smith”. Where it is clear, enter the married surname first.</p>

      <h4>Forename(s)</h4>

      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong>
</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="guide">Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Copy forenames as they appear on the census page — even if they look wrong, or are known to be wrong!  Type abbreviated names as recorded: do not, for example, expand “Thos” to “Thomas” or “Margt” to “Margaret”. Do not put a “.” after an abbreviated forename.&#160;</p>
      <p>Allow one space between any names, initials, or words.&#160;</p>
      <p>You <em>must</em> enter something in this column for everyone in a household. Where no forename has been recorded, you should enter “-” (a hyphen) in cthis column.</p>
      <p>Type any titles after forenames and enclose in brackets (parentheses): for example, “Mary (Mrs)”, “Charles (Rev)”, “Wm (Dr)”, “John (Prof)”, “Elizabeth (Lady Chalfont)”, etc.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Scotland</h5>
      <p>??? If the enumerator has put “unbaptised”, or “infant”, or not recorded a name for an child under one year, put “(Unnamed)”.</p>

      <h4>Name Query</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> if you have doubts about the interpretation of the names in either field "Surname" or field "Forename". Write a brief comment in the "Transcriber Notes" column to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?forename”&#160;&#160;</p>

      <h4>Relationship to Head</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>

      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the relationship recorded on the census page.</p>
      <p>If no relationship is shown on the census page, enter “-” (a hyphen).  Please note that the <strong>1841</strong> Census did not record this information, and this column can be left blank.</p>

      <h4>(Marital) Status</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>The entry can be one character (<strong>m</strong>, <strong>s</strong>, <strong>u</strong> or <strong>w</strong>)</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the marital status recorded on the census page as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter <strong>m</strong> where the status is indicated as married</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>s</strong> where the status is indicated as single (1891 only)</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>u</strong> where the status is indicated as unmarried (1851, 1861 and 1871)</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>w</strong> where the status is indicated as widowed</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If no status is recorded, enter “-” (a hyphen). The <strong>1841</strong> census did not record this information, and this column can be left blank.</p>

      <h4>Gender Male/Female</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and is a single character (<strong>m</strong> or <strong>f</strong>)</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The enumerator was required to enter the age of a person in one of two columns on the census page, headed Male and Female.  FreeCEN transcribes this as a single letter, <strong>m</strong> or <strong>f</strong>.  Where the age is missing, you should normally enter a hyphen.</p>
      <p>You should transcribe the gender according to the column in which the enumerator has entered the age, even where this appears to be wrong according to the relationship to the head of the household (e.g. a daughter noted as male). You can leave a note of explanation in the Transcriber’s notes to call attention to the discrepancy. </p>

      <h4>Age</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry here is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 3 numerals plus a single character (<strong>y</strong>, <strong>m</strong>, <strong>w</strong> or <strong>d</strong>), <strong>###a</strong> </li>
        <li>Do not put a space between the number and the letter</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      Requirements:<br /><ul><li>An entry here is required and can be up to 3 numerals plus a single character (y, m, w or d), ###a&#160;</li>
<li>Do not put a space between the number and the letter</li>
</ul>Guidance:<br />Enter the age as shown on the census page, applying the following rules:<br /><p>Where the age is shown in years, enter the number of years. There is no need to enter y for years, as this will be automatically assumed in the FreeCEN process. Any number between 1 and 120 will be accepted. Ignore any fractions of years over 2 years, and add the further detail in Transcribers notes Any fractions of less than 2 years should be converted to months. For any age in years that includes a fraction, put the whole number in field "Age", and the full entry in Transcriber’s Notes: for example, for a stated age of 7½, put “7” in field "Age" and “Age 7.5” in field "Transcribers notes"</p>
<p>Where the age is shown in months, enter the number followed by m. Any number between 1 and 24 will be accepted. Where the age in months exceeds 24, round the figure down to years, and add the further detail in the "Census notes column.</p>Where the age is shown in weeks, enter the number followed by w. Any number between 1 and 20 will be accepted.<br />Where the age is shown in days, enter the number followed by d. Any number between 1 and 30 will be accepted.<br />If the age is shown as “less than 1 month”, enter as “1m”.<br /><p>If no age is shown, or the figure is unreadable, enter&#160; 999. It is not acceptable to enter “0” (zero) or “-” (a hyphen).&#160;</p>

      <h4>Demographic Query</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>The entry may be a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or the column may be left blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> in this where you have doubts about the interpretation of any of the "Relationship to Head", "Status", "Gender" or "Age" columns&#160; whether because you cannot read or for other reasons. Write a brief comment in the "Transcriber Notes" column to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?age”&#160;&#160;</p>
    </div>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <div id="job">
      <h3>Rank, Profession or Occupation</h3>

      <div class="push--bottom"> Return to <a href="#index">On this page</a> </div>

      <h4>Occupation</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>-</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The general approach to transcribing occupations should be to copy what appears on the census page.  However, census enumerators were given permission to abbreviate a number of common occupations, and it is FreeCEN policy to expand these to assist the researcher where we can be sure of the meaning intended. [may be amended after consultation with developers story #</p>
<p>Where the enumerator has used a repeater word or mark (such as “ditto” or “do”), the occupation must be copied from the preceding entry.</p>
      <p><span style="color: rgb(60, 120, 180); font-size: 1.8rem;">Employer</span>
</p>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>e</strong>) or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>

      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The employment category only appears in the <strong>1891</strong> Census.  Otherwise this column may be left blank.</p>
      
      <h4>Employmee</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>r </strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>

      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The employment category only appears in the <strong>1891</strong> Census.  Otherwise this column may be left blank.</p>
      
      <h4>Neither Employer nor Employee</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>n</strong>) if this box is marked, otherwise&#160; leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>

      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The employment category only appears in the <strong>1891</strong> Census.  Otherwise this column may be left blank.</p>
      <p><span style="color: rgb(60, 120, 180); font-size: 1.8rem;">Work Query</span>
</p>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> in in this column where you have doubts about the interpretation of&#160; the "Occupation", "Employer", "Employee" or "Neither e nor e" either because you cannot read or for other reasons. Write a brief comment in the "Transcriber Notes" column to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?occupation: possibly Limner”</p>
    
    </div> 
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <div id="birthplace">
      <h3>Birthplace &amp; Sundries</h3>

      <div class="push--bottom">Return to <a href="#pageNav">On this page</a> </div>

      <h4>Where Born County [PoB Chapman Code]</h4>
<p><span style="color: rgb(60, 120, 180);">Requirements:</span>
</p>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and takes the form of a three-letter Chapman Code</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The entry in this column must be taken from the list of Chapman Codes in <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#chapman">Appendix 3</a>.  Enter the county (or country) as it appears on the census page, even where it may appear to be wrong.  Where no county is recorded, you should only enter one if the <em>Place</em> of birth leaves no doubts. Remember that many British place names appear in more than one county.</p>
      <p>Where the place of birth is outside the British Isles:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter “OVB” if the person is stated to be a British subject</li>
        <li>Enter “OVF” if the person is not stated to be a British subject <em>and</em> was born in any other foreign country</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="islet islet--bordered"><p>The <strong>British Isles</strong> of the 19<sup>th</sup> Century consisted of England, Ireland, Scotland, Wales, the Isle of Man and the Channel Isles: naturally, none of these places counts as overseas for any of the censuses we are transcribing.</p>
<p>If the place of birth is given as England, Wales, Scotland, London, Isle of Wight, Ireland, Jersey, Guernsey, Sark, etc., with&#160; no further detail, use the correct Chapman code for that country in this field.&#160;&#160;</p>
<p>However, make sure that you use a county code, rather than a country code, where one is available, even if the original gives both a county and a country.&#160; E.g.&#160;for a person born in Youghal, County Cork, Ireland, . This should be entered as Chapman Code COR not Chapman Code IRL. Ireland is understood from the fact that the Chapman Code is Co Cork and so is not needed.&#160;</p> </div>

      <p>Where no county or country is shown, or where there is any doubt about what should be entered, then enter “UNK”.  If necessary, please add a note of explanation in the "Transcriber notes" column.</p>
      <p>Special rules apply for the <strong>1841</strong> Census, where the questions asked were whether the person was born in the same county, and if not whether the person was born in another country of the British Isles or in Foreign Parts.  The rules to be applied for the 1841 Census are as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>If born in the same county, enter the Chapman Code for that County</li>
        <li>If born out of the county, enter “OUC”</li>
        <li>If born in another country of the British Isles, enter the Chapman Code for that country</li>
        <li>If born in Foreign Parts, enter “OVF”</li>
        <li>If the enumerator recorded another specific county, then enter that Chapman Code</li>
        <li>If there was no indication of place of birth or it is unclear what should be entered, then enter “UNK”</li>
      </ul>
    </div> 
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />    
      <h4>Where born Place</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 20 characters</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the place of birth as it is written on the census page.  Do not attempt to correct or modernise the spelling of place names. If you believe the spelling should be corrected, then enter an "x" in the "PoB Query" column and type the 'correct' place name into the "Normalised Place of Birth" column.</p>
<p>If the original gives a county and a country, do not put either in this field, if there is an appropriate county code - e.g. Co Cork, Youghal. This should be entered in the previous field as Chapman Code COR, and this field used only for the locality within the county - e.g. Youghal &#160;</p>
<p>If the place of birth is given as England, Wales, Scotland, London, Isle of Wight, Ireland, Jersey, Guernsey, Sark, etc., use the correct Chapman code for the country, in the preceding field and a hyphen (“-”) in this field, if no further detail is given.</p>
<p>If no place of birth is indicated (other than possibly a county or country, for which you enter the Chapman Code in&#160; "Where born County"), then enter “-” (a hyphen).&#160;</p>
<p>&#160;The <strong>1841</strong> Census did not record the place of birth, and this column can be left blank.</p>
      <p><span style="color: rgb(60, 120, 180); font-size: 1.8rem;">PoB Query</span>
</p>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> in this column where you have doubts about the interpretation of either of the "County of Birth" or "Place of Birth" colunns either because you cannot read or for other reasons. Write a brief comment in the&#160; "Transcriber notes" column to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?county may be Sussex, not Surrey - see [name of gazetteer where you have identified the place name is unique to Sussex]”&#160;</p>
    
      <h4>Disability</h4>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the information shown on the census page.</p>
      <p>This information was not recorded in the <strong>1841</strong> Census, and column W can be left blank.</p>
    
      <h4>Welsh Spoken</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>w</strong>, <strong>e</strong> or <strong>b</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>This information was only collected in the <strong>1891</strong> Census in Welsh Counties. Otherwise, column X may be left blank. Where appropriate, enter the information on the census page as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter <strong>w</strong> if only Welsh spoken</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>e</strong> if only English spoken</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>b</strong> if both Welsh and English spoken</li>
        <li>Leave column X blank if the information was not recorded</li>
      </ul>
    
    </div> 
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <div id="notes">
      <h3>Notes &amp; <q>Mynotes</q> </h3>
      <div class="push--bottom">Return to <a href="#pageNav">On this page</a> </div>


<h4>Census Notes
      </h4>
<h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column should have two parts for each note, the field to which it pertains, and the Note, which should be typed as seen.</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
<h4>Transcriber Notes</h4>
<p>This column is used to enter additional information as which cannot be accommodated in the columns.&#160; Note the location of the entry (if in one column), and type what you see after a colon, e.g.&#160; 'Age: smudged : possibly 52?' or 'gender: f. but relationship is s',. You can also use it to record the number of rooms with windows, where stated: for example, “3 rooms”.&#160;</p>
      <p>This field replaces the 'mynotes.txt' used in FreeCEN1.</p>
<h4>Proofreaders Notes</h4>
<p>Identify field, then note issue/resolution e.g. 'Age: resolved as 58'&#160;</p>
<h4>Validator Notes</h4>
<p>Identify field, then note issue/resolution e.g. 'Place of birth: normalised as Swinton near Malton, but may be another Swinton in North Yorkshire'</p>
<h4>"Correct" Place of Birth</h4>
<p>Use to record a normalised spelling of a Place of Birth - e.g. 'Floor' (Northamptonshire village) where the original has 'Flower'.&#160; This field will be used to enable the place to be found even with 'incorrect' spelling.</p>

    
      
    </div> 
